ce:section.ce:para:
In 2022, Li et al. [78] successfully established a ratiometric fluorescence method for sensitive detection of alkaline phosphatase (ALP) based on dual-emission system of CDs-Ag+- OPD (Scheme 13
                        ). In this system, CDs exhibits a blue fluorescence emission at 454 nm and OPD is oxidized by Ag+ to yield yellow DAP with emission peak at 570 nm, when excited at 360 nm. AA, which is produced by the catalysis reaction of ALP and 2-phospho-l-ascorbic acid (AAP), can react with Ag+ to generate dehydroascorbic acid (DHAA). Subsequently, the generated DHAA can react with OPD to further form a blue emission product of quoxaline (QX). Thus, it results in fluorescence intensity decrease at 570 nm and increase at 454 on the basis of IFE and FRET. Then, the linear relationship between the concentration of ALP and ratio of fluorescence intensity (F

                           454

                        /F

                           570
                        ) is obtained, with detection limit of 0.1 U/L.
